# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: antimicrobial-resistance
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/2016-united-states-federal-budget] The United States Federal Budget for fiscal year 2016 began as a budget proposed by President Barack Obama to fund government operations for October 1, 2015 – September 30, 2016.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/2016-united-states-federal-budget] The requested budget was submitted to the 114th Congress on February 2, 2015.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/2016-united-states-federal-budget] The government was initially funded through a series of three temporary continuing resolutions.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/2016-united-states-federal-budget] The final funding package was passed as an omnibus spending bill, the Consolidated Appropriations Act, 2016, enacted on December 18, 2015.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/2016-united-states-federal-budget] The Budget Control Act of 2011 (BCA) had established spending caps on defense and non-defense spending.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/2016-united-states-federal-budget] These were first applied in FY2013; they resulted in across-the-board sequestration cuts because that budget was funded through a full-year continuing resolution that exceeded the budget caps.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/2016-united-states-federal-budget] The Bipartisan Budget Act of 2013 increased the budget caps for FY2014 and FY2015 by $45 billion and $18 billion, respectively.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/2016-united-states-federal-budget] Concern was expressed that the BCA caps for defense were far below the Obama administration's budget request and would lead to cuts relative to these increased levels.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/2016-united-states-federal-budget] Although the word "sequestration" was widely applied to refer to these cuts, even a continuing resolution would not cause another round of across-the-board sequestration cuts as in 2013 because the FY2016 discretionary defense cap is still slightly larger than the FY2015 cap in nominal terms.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/2016-united-states-federal-budget] The budget and appropriations legislation will be the first passed since Republicans gained majorities in both houses of the United States Congress in the 2014 midterm elections.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/2016-united-states-federal-budget] The Obama administration's budget was transmitted to Congress on February 2, 2015.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/2016-united-states-federal-budget] The administration requested funding levels for discretionary spending that were 7% over the budget caps specified in the Budget Control Act of 2011, roughly equally split between defense and non-defense programs.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/2016-united-states-federal-budget] It envisioned large tax increases on corporations and the wealthy, which were expected to be opposed by Congress, to fund programs in education and infrastructure.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/2016-united-states-federal-budget] Congress passed its budget resolution in May 2015.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/2016-united-states-federal-budget] It was the first budget resolution successfully passed by Congress in over five years.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/2016-united-states-federal-budget] Congressional budget resolutions are non-binding and largely symbolic, in that the actual spending levels are specified in much greater detail in the appropriations bills to be passed later in the year.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/2016-united-states-federal-budget] The bill envisioned increasing military spending and decreasing social programs, with the goal of having a balanced budget by 2025.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/2016-united-states-federal-budget] The passage of a budget resolution opened the way for budget reconciliation procedures to be used to repeal the Affordable Care Act on a simple majority vote, although a presidential veto of such legislation was expected.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/2016-united-states-federal-budget] It was expected that a continuing resolution would be required to fund the government past October 1, 2015.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/2016-united-states-federal-budget] However, conservative Republicans were expected to oppose any funding bill that did not defund Planned Parenthood as a result of the recent controversy.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/2016-united-states-federal-budget] However, the Continuing Appropriations Resolution, 2016 was passed on September 30, 2015, funding the government through December 11 at roughly the same levels as FY2015, without any other policy provisions favored by conservatives.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/2016-united-states-federal-budget] The bill was passed in large part due to the announcement a week earlier of John Boehner's resignation as Speaker of the House.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/2016-united-states-federal-budget] The House passed the Restoring Americans' Healthcare Freedom Reconciliation Act of 2015 on October 23, 2015, under the budget reconciliation process, which prevents the possibility of a filibuster in the Senate.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/2016-united-states-federal-budget] The bill would partially repeal the provisions of the Affordable Care Act, notably the individual and employer mandates as well as the taxes on Cadillac insurance plans.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/2016-united-states-federal-budget] Some conservatives in both the House and Senate opposed the bill because it did not completely repeal the Affordable Care Act, which would have been inconsistent with the rules governing budget reconciliation bills.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/2016-united-states-federal-budget] The bill was the 61st time that the House had voted to fully or partially repeal the Affordable Care act.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/2016-united-states-federal-budget] The bill also would remove federal funding for Planned Parenthood for one year.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/2016-united-states-federal-budget] The bill was expected to be vetoed by President Obama should it pass the Senate.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/2016-united-states-federal-budget] Just before midnight on October 26, 2015, Republican and Democratic leaders reached an agreement to increase the budget caps imposed by the Budget Control Act of 2011 for fiscal years 2016 and 2017, and temporarily suspend the debt limit until March 15, 2017.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/2016-united-states-federal-budget] The agreement authorizes $80 billion in increased spending over two years, which is to be offset by changes in Medicare, Social Security disability insurance, selling off oil from the strategic petroleum reserves, and other changes.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/2016-united-states-federal-budget] The deal also repeals a provision of the Affordable Care Act, not yet in effect, which would require businesses that offer one or more health plans and have more than 200 employees to automatically enroll new full-time employees in a health plan.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/2016-united-states-federal-budget] John Boehner said the compromise was intended to "clean out the barn" before Paul Ryan took over as Speaker of the House.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/2016-united-states-federal-budget] The bill, the Bipartisan Budget Act of 2015, passed the House with a vote of 266–167, with just over two-thirds of Republicans voting against the bill, and all Democrats and the remaining Republicans voting for passage, with one not voting.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/2016-united-states-federal-budget] The bill passed the Senate with a vote of 64–35, with 35 Republicans voting against.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/2016-united-states-federal-budget] It was signed by the President on November 2, 2015.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/2016-united-states-federal-budget] The Treasury had estimated that extraordinary measures used to fund the government beyond October 1 would likely be exhausted no later than November 3.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/2016-united-states-federal-budget] Congress passed a five-day extension of the continuing resolution on December 11, 2015.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/2016-united-states-federal-budget] A bipartisan deal to pass the appropriations legislation, the Consolidated Appropriations Act, 2016, was announced on December 15.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/2016-united-states-federal-budget] In early December, the Senate passed an amended version of the healthcare reconciliation bill, sending it back to the House.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/2016-united-states-federal-budget] It was passed by the House on January 6, 2016, and vetoed by President Obama on January 8, only the sixth veto of his presidency.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/2016-united-states-federal-budget] The House failed to override the President's veto on February on a vote of 241–186, which did not meet the required two-thirds supermajority.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/79th-united-nations-general-assembly] The **Seventy-ninth session of the United Nations General Assembly** was the session of the United Nations General Assembly that ran from 10 September 2024 to 9 September 2025.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/79th-united-nations-general-assembly] The president of the General Assembly was from the African Group.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/79th-united-nations-general-assembly] On 6 June 2024, the former Prime Minister of Cameroon, Philémon Yang, was elected by acclamation to the position of President of the General Assembly.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/79th-united-nations-general-assembly] Each member of the General Assembly had a representative speaking about issues concerning their country and the hopes for the coming year as to what the UNGA would do.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/79th-united-nations-general-assembly] This is an opportunity for the member states to opine on international issues of their concern.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/79th-united-nations-general-assembly] The order of speakers is given first to member states, then observer states and supranational bodies.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/79th-united-nations-general-assembly] Any other observers entities have a chance to speak at the end of the debate, if they so choose.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/79th-united-nations-general-assembly] Speakers will be put on the list in the order of their request, with special consideration for ministers and other government officials of similar or higher rank.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/79th-united-nations-general-assembly] According to the rules in place for the General Debate, the statements should be in of the United Nations official languages of Arabic, Chinese, English, French, Russian or Spanish, and is translated by the United Nations translators.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/79th-united-nations-general-assembly] Each speaker is requested to provide 350 advance copies of their statements to the conference officers to facilitate translation and to be presented at the podium.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/absorption-pharmacology] The drug travels by some route of administration (oral, topical-dermal, etc.) in a chosen dosage form (e.g., tablets, capsules, or in solution).
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/absorption-pharmacology] Absorption by some other routes, such as intravenous therapy, intramuscular injection, enteral nutrition, is even more straightforward and there is less variability in absorption and bioavailability is often near 100%.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/absorption-pharmacology] Intravascular administration does not involve absorption, and there is no loss of drug.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/absorption-pharmacology] The fastest route of absorption is inhalation.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/absorption-pharmacology] Absorption is a primary focus in drug development and medicinal chemistry, since a drug must be absorbed before any medicinal effects can occur.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/absorption-pharmacology] Moreover, the drug's pharmacokinetic profile can be easily and significantly changed by adjusting factors that affect absorption.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/absorption-pharmacology] Oral ingestion is the most common route of administration of pharmaceuticals.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/absorption-pharmacology] Passing through the esophagus to the stomach, the contents of the capsule or tablet are absorbed by the GI tract.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/absorption-pharmacology] The absorbed pharmaceutical is then passed through the liver and kidneys.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/absorption-pharmacology] The rate of dissolution is a key target for controlling the duration of a drug's effect, and as such, several dosage forms that contain the same active ingredient may be available, differing only in the rate of dissolution.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/absorption-pharmacology] If a drug is supplied in a form that is not readily dissolved, it may be released gradually and act for longer.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/absorption-pharmacology] Having a longer duration of action may improve compliance since the medication will not have to be taken as often.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/absorption-pharmacology] Additionally, slow-release dosage forms may maintain concentrations within an acceptable therapeutic range over a longer period, whereas quick-release dosage forms may have sharper peaks and troughs in serum concentration.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/absorption-pharmacology] As can be inferred from the Noyes–Whitney equation, the rate of dissolution may be modified primarily by altering the surface area of the solid by altering the particle size (e.g., with micronization).
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/absorption-pharmacology] For many drugs, reducing the particle size reduces the dose needed to achieve the same therapeutic effect.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/absorption-pharmacology] The particle size reduction increases the specific surface area and the dissolution rate and does not affect solubility.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/absorption-pharmacology] The rate of dissolution may also be altered by choosing a suitable polymorph of a compound.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/absorption-pharmacology] Different polymorphs have different solubility and dissolution rate characteristics.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/absorption-pharmacology] Specifically, crystalline forms dissolve slower than amorphous forms since they require more energy to leave the lattice during dissolution.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/absorption-pharmacology] The stablest crystalline polymorph has the lowest dissolution rate.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/absorption-pharmacology] Dissolution also differs between anhydrous and hydrous forms of a drug.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/absorption-pharmacology] Anhydrous forms often dissolve faster but sometimes are less soluble.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/absorption-pharmacology] Esterification is also used to control solubility.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/absorption-pharmacology] For example, stearate and estolate esters of drugs have decreased solubility in gastric fluid.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/absorption-pharmacology] Later, esterases in the gastrointestinal tract (GIT) wall and blood hydrolyze these esters to release the parent drug.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/absorption-pharmacology] Coatings on a tablet or pellet may act as barriers to reducing the dissolution rate.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/absorption-pharmacology] Coatings may also be used to control where dissolution takes place.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/absorption-pharmacology] For example, enteric coatings only dissolve in the basic environment of the intestines.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/absorption-pharmacology] Drugs held in solution do not need to be dissolved before being absorbed.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/absorption-pharmacology] Lipid-soluble drugs are absorbed more rapidly than water-soluble drugs.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/absorption-pharmacology] The gastrointestinal tract is lined with epithelial cells.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/absorption-pharmacology] Drugs must pass through or permeate these cells to be absorbed into the bloodstream.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/absorption-pharmacology] Cell membranes may act as barriers to some drugs.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/absorption-pharmacology] They are essentially lipid bilayers which form semipermeable membranes.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/absorption-pharmacology] Pure lipid bilayers are generally permeable only to small, uncharged solutes.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/absorption-pharmacology] Hence, whether or not a molecule is ionized will affect its absorption, since ionic molecules are charged.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/absorption-pharmacology] Solubility favors charged species, and permeability favors neutral species.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/absorption-pharmacology] Some molecules have special exchange proteins and channels to facilitate movement from the lumen into the circulation.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/absorption-pharmacology] The fatty acid chains repel ionized, charged molecules.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/absorption-pharmacology] This means that the ionized molecules cannot pass through the intestinal membrane and be absorbed.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/absorption-pharmacology] The Henderson-Hasselbalch equation offers a way to determine the proportion of a substance that is ionized at a given pH.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/absorption-pharmacology] In the stomach, drugs that are weak acids (such as aspirin) will be present mainly in their non-ionic form, and weak bases will be in their ionic form.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/absorption-pharmacology] Since non-ionic species diffuse more readily through cell membranes, weak acids will have a higher absorption in the highly acidic stomach.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/absorption-pharmacology] However, the reverse is true in the basic environment of the intestines—weak bases (such as caffeine) will diffuse more readily since they will be non-ionic.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/absorption-pharmacology] This aspect of absorption has been targeted by medicinal chemists.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/absorption-pharmacology] For example, they may choose an analog that is more likely to be in a non-ionic form.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/absorption-pharmacology] Also, the chemists may develop prodrugs of a compound—these chemical variants may be more readily absorbed and then metabolized by the body into the active compound.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/absorption-pharmacology] However, changing the structure of a molecule is less predictable than altering dissolution properties, since changes in chemical structure may affect the pharmacodynamic properties of a drug.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/absorption-pharmacology] The solubility and permeability of a drug candidate are important physicochemical properties the scientist wants to know as early as possible.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acetylation] In chemistry, **acetylation** is an organic esterification reaction with acetic acid.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acetylation] It introduces an acetyl group into a chemical compound.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acetylation] Such compounds are termed *acetate esters* or simply *acetates*.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acetylation] **Deacetylation** is the opposite reaction, the removal of an acetyl group from a chemical compound.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acetylation] Histone deacetylases "play crucial roles in gene transcription and most likely in all eukaryotic biological processes that involve chromatin".
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acetylation] Acetylation is one type of post-translational modification of proteins.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acetylation] The acetylation of the ε-amino group of lysine, which is common, converts a charged side chain to a neutral one.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acetylation] Acetylation/deacetylation of histones also plays a role in gene expression and cancer.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acetylation] These modifications are effected by enzymes called histone acetyltransferases (HATs) and histone deacetylases (HDACs).
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acetylation] Two general mechanisms are known for deacetylation.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acetylation] One mechanism involves zinc binding to the acetyl oxygen.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acetylation] Another family of deacetylases require NAD+, which transfers an ribosyl group to the acetyl oxygen.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acetylation] Acetate esters and acetamides are generally prepared by acetylations.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acetylation] Acetylations are often used in making C-acetyl bonds in Friedel-Crafts reactions.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acetylation] Carbanions and their equivalents are susceptible to acetylations.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acetylation] Cellulose is a polyol and thus susceptible to acetylation, which is achieved using acetic anhydride.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acetylation] Acetylation disrupts hydrogen bonding, which otherwise dominates the properties of cellulose.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acetylation] Consequently, the cellulose esters are soluble in organic solvents and can be cast into fibers and films.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acetylation] Acetylation of wood is a chemical modification process that enhances the properties of wood by making it highly resistant to fungi and insects, as well as very durable against moisture and environmental parameters.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acetylation] The process involves the chemical reaction of acetic anhydride with the free hydroxyl groups in wood polymers, mostly of lignin and hemicelluloses, without requiring a catalyst.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acetylation] The modification results in bonds between the structural polymeric components, significantly reducing the ability of the -OH groups to form hydrogen bonds with water molecules.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acetylation] This effectively "locks" the cellular walls, minimizing the capacity of wood to absorb water and enhancing its dimensional stability.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acetylation] Approximately 80-90% of the hydroxyl groups of wood are modified during the process.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acetylation] The whole process is an environmentally friendly treatment, and has emerged, in the 21st century, as a significant innovation in the scientific area of wood science.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acetylation] Transacetylation uses vinyl acetate as an acetyl donor and lipase as a catalyst.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acetylation] This methodology allows the preparation of enantio-enriched alcohols and acetates.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acinetobacter-baumannii] Bacteria of this genus lack flagella but exhibit twitching or swarming motility, likely mediated by type IV pili.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acinetobacter-baumannii] Motility in *A. baumannii* may also be due to the excretion of exopolysaccharide, creating a film of high-molecular-weight sugar chains behind the bacterium to move forward.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acinetobacter-baumannii] Clinical microbiologists typically differentiate members of the genus *Acinetobacter* from other Moraxellaceae by performing an oxidase test, as *Acinetobacter* spp. are the only members of the Moraxellaceae to lack cytochrome c oxidases.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acinetobacter-baumannii] *A. baumannii* is strictly aerobic, meaning it needs oxygen to grow.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acinetobacter-baumannii] Baumannii* is able to survive in varying levels of oxygen, including no oxygen, by entering a dormant state.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acinetobacter-baumannii] Colloquially, *A. baumannii* is referred to as "**Iraqibacter**" due to its seemingly sudden emergence in military treatment facilities during the Iraq War.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acinetobacter-baumannii] It has continued to be an issue for veterans and soldiers who served in Iraq and Afghanistan.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acinetobacter-baumannii] Multidrug-resistant *A. baumannii* has spread to civilian hospitals in part due to the transport of infected soldiers through multiple medical facilities.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acinetobacter-baumannii] During the COVID-19 pandemic, coinfection with *A. baumannii* secondary to SARS-CoV-2 infections has been reported multiple times in medical publications.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acinetobacter-baumannii] Adhesion can be a critical determinant of virulence for bacteria.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acinetobacter-baumannii] The ability to attach to host cells allows bacteria to interact with them in various ways, whether by type III secretion system or simply by holding on against the prevailing movement of fluids.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acinetobacter-baumannii] Outer membrane protein A (OmpA) has been shown to be involved in the adherence of *A. baumannii* to epithelial cells.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acinetobacter-baumannii] This allows the bacteria to invade the cells through the zipper mechanism.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acinetobacter-baumannii] The protein was also shown to localize to the mitochondria of epithelial cells.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acinetobacter-baumannii] OmpA attachment to mitochondria induces it leading to swelling of mitochondria.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acinetobacter-baumannii] This releases cytochrome c, which causes formation of apoptosome.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acinetobacter-baumannii] This leads to the apoptosis of the cell.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acinetobacter-baumannii] Mechanisms of antibiotic resistance can be categorized into three groups.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acinetobacter-baumannii] First, resistance can be achieved by reducing membrane permeability or increasing efflux of the antibiotic and thus preventing access to the target.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acinetobacter-baumannii] Second, bacteria can protect the antibiotic target through genetic mutation or post-translational modification.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acinetobacter-baumannii] Third, antibiotics can be directly inactivated by hydrolysis or modification.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acinetobacter-baumannii] One of the most important weapons in the armoury of *Acinetobacter* is its impressive genetic plasticity, facilitating rapid genetic mutations and rearrangements as well as integration of foreign determinants carried by mobile genetic elements.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acinetobacter-baumannii] Of these, insertion sequences are considered one of the key forces shaping bacterial genomes and ultimately evolution.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acinetobacter-baumannii] Pathogenicity islands, relatively common genetic structures in bacterial pathogens, are composed of two or more adjacent genes that increase a pathogen's virulence.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acinetobacter-baumannii] They may contain genes that encode toxins, coagulate blood, or as in this case, allow the bacteria to resist antibiotics.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acinetobacter-baumannii] AbaR-type resistance islands are typical of drug-resistant *A. baumannii*, and different variations may be present in a given strain.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acinetobacter-baumannii] Each consists of a transposon backbone of about 16.3 Kb that facilitates horizontal gene transfer.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acinetobacter-baumannii] This makes horizontal gene transfer of this and similar pathogenicity islands more likely because, when genetic material is taken up by a new bacterium, the transposons allow the pathogenicity island to integrate into the new microorganism's genome.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acinetobacter-baumannii] In this case, it would grant the new microorganism the potential to resist certain antibiotics.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acinetobacter-baumannii] Antibiotic resistance genes are commonly transferred between Gram-negative bacteria through plasmids via conjugation, which accelerates the appearance of new resistant strains.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acinetobacter-baumannii] AbaR's contain several genes for antibiotic resistance, all flanked by insertion sequences.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acinetobacter-baumannii] Conjugation experiments demonstrated that the *blaOXA-23*, *blaPER-1*, and *aphA6* genes could be successfully transferred between the clinical and the environmental isolates via the plasmid group GR6 or class 1 integrons through in vitro conjugation.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acinetobacter-baumannii] In collaboration with some other genes, they provide resistance to aminoglycosides, aminocyclitols, tetracycline, and chloramphenicol.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acinetobacter-baumannii] Efflux pumps are protein machines that use energy to pump antibiotics and other small molecules that get into the bacterial cytoplasm and the periplasmic space out of the cell.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acinetobacter-baumannii] By constantly pumping antibiotics out of the cell, bacteria can increase the concentration of a given antibiotic required to kill them or inhibit their growth when the target of the antibiotic is inside the bacterium.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acinetobacter-baumannii] *A. baumannii* is known to have two major efflux pumps which decrease its susceptibility to antimicrobials.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acinetobacter-baumannii] The first, AdeB, has been shown to be responsible for aminoglycoside resistance.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acinetobacter-baumannii] The second, AdeDE, is responsible for efflux of a wide range of substrates, including tetracycline, chloramphenicol, and various carbapenems.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acinetobacter-baumannii] Many other efflux pumps have been implicated in *A. baumannii* resistant strains.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acinetobacter-baumannii] Bacterial small RNAs are noncoding RNAs that regulate various cellular processes.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acinetobacter-baumannii] Three sRNAs, AbsR11, AbsR25, and AbsR28, have been experimentally validated in the MTCC 1425 (ATCC15308) strain, which is a (multidrug-resistant) strain showing resistance to 12 antibiotics.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acinetobacter-baumannii] AbsR25 sRNA could play a role in the efflux pump regulation and drug resistance.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acinetobacter-baumannii] The formation of biofilm involves cell attachment, a fundamental process typically triggered by environmental metabolites.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acinetobacter-baumannii] *A. baumannii* is able to use vanillic acid as its sole carbon source, like its close relative *A. baylyi*.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acinetobacter-baumannii] This metabolic pathway is regulated by transcriptional repressor VanR.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acinetobacter-baumannii] When vanillic acid enters the cell through VanP and VanK porins it binds to the VanR regulator, which is usually bound to P*vanABKP* and P*csu* promoters.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acinetobacter-baumannii] This binding causes repression of P*vanABKP* and P*csu* promoters, which leads to increased expression of VanP and VanK porins in the cell membrane and increased expression of Csu pili.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acinetobacter-baumannii] The increased expression of Csu pili results a high biofilm formation phenotype of *A. baumannii*.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acinetobacter-baumannii] Recent computational studies using genome-scale metabolic models (such as iCN718) have examined how *Acinetobacter baumannii* adapts to host environments.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acinetobacter-baumannii] Graph-based analyses of metabolic networks indicate that metabolite accessibility differs between laboratory and infection-like conditions, including modeled wound and lung infection site environments.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acinetobacter-baumannii] Research and computational iterations suggest the membrane biosynthesis pathways and phosphate-dependent processes become more constrained during infection, highlighting potential environment-specific metabolic vulnerabilities.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acinetobacter-baumannii] Symptoms of *A. baumannii* infections are often indistinguishable from other opportunistic infections caused by other opportunistic bacteria - including *Klebsiella pneumoniae* and *Streptococcus pneumoniae*.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acinetobacter-baumannii] In some cases, *A. baumannii* may present no infection or symptoms, as with colonizing an open wound or tracheostomy site.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acinetobacter-baumannii] Because most infections are now resistant to multiple drugs, determining what susceptibilities the particular strain has is necessary for treatment to be successful.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acinetobacter-baumannii] Traditionally, infections were treated with imipenem or meropenem, but a steady rise in carbapenem-resistant *A. baumannii* has been noted.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acinetobacter-baumannii] Consequently, treatment methods often fall back on polymyxins, particularly colistin although tetracyclines have shown promise in MDR *A. baumannii*.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acinetobacter-baumannii] Colistin is considered a drug of last resort because it often causes kidney damage, among other side effects.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acinetobacter-baumannii] Prevention methods in hospitals focus on increased hand-washing and more diligent sterilization procedures.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acinetobacter-baumannii] An *A. baumannii* infection was recently treated using phage therapy.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acinetobacter-baumannii] Phages are viruses that attack bacteria, and have also been demonstrated to resensitize *A. baumannii* to antibiotics it normally resists.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acinetobacter-baumannii] Scientists at MIT, Harvard's Broad Institute and MIT's CSAIL found a compound named halicin using deep learning that can effectively kill *A. baumannii*.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acinetobacter-baumannii] The candidate drug abaucin has narrow-spectrum effectiveness.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acinetobacter-baumannii] Zosurabalpin kills *A. baumannii,* is effective in animal models, and is currently in Phase I clinical trials.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acinetobacter-baumannii] American and other western soldiers in Iraq and Afghanistan were at risk of traumatic injury due to gunfire and improvised explosive devices.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acinetobacter-baumannii] Previously, infection was thought to occur due to contamination with *A. baumannii* at the time of injury.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acinetobacter-baumannii] Injured soldiers were first taken to level-I facilities, where they were stabilized.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acinetobacter-baumannii] Depending on the severity of the injury, the soldiers might then be transferred to a level-II facility, which consists of a forward surgical team, for additional stabilization.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acinetobacter-baumannii] Depending on the logistics of the locality, the injured soldiers might be transfer between these facilities several times before finally being taken to a major hospital within the combat zone (level III).
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acinetobacter-baumannii] Generally after 1–3 days, when the patients were stabilized, they were transferred by air to a regional facility (level IV) for additional treatment.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acinetobacter-baumannii] For soldiers serving in Iraq or Afghanistan, this was typically Landstuhl Regional Medical Center in Germany.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acinetobacter-baumannii] Finally, the injured soldiers were transferred to hospitals in their home country for rehabilitation and additional treatment.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acinetobacter-baumannii] This repeated exposure to many different medical environments seems to be the reason *A. baumannii* infections have become increasingly common.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acinetobacter-baumannii] Multidrug-resistant *A. baumannii* is a major factor in complicating the treatment and rehabilitation of injured soldiers, and has led to additional deaths.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acinetobacter-baumannii] Being referred to as an opportunistic infection, *A. baumannii* infections are highly prevalent in hospital settings.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acinetobacter-baumannii] The importation of *A. baumannii* and subsequent presence in hospitals has been well documented.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acinetobacter-baumannii] *A. baumannii* is usually introduced into a hospital by a colonized patient.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acinetobacter-baumannii] Due to its ability to survive on artificial surfaces and resist desiccation, it can remain and possibly infect new patients for some time.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acinetobacter-baumannii] *A baumannii* growth is suspected to be favored in hospital settings due to the constant use of antibiotics by patients in the hospital.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acinetobacter-baumannii] Acinetobacter can be spread by person-to-person contact or contact with contaminated surfaces.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acinetobacter-baumannii] *Acinetobacter* can enter through open wounds, catheters and breathing tubes.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/acinetobacter-baumannii] In a study of European intensive care units in 2009, *A. baumannii* was found to be responsible for 19.1% of ventilator-associated pneumonia cases.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/adme] ADME describes the disposition of a pharmaceutical compound within an organism.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/adme] The four criteria all influence the drug levels and kinetics of drug exposure to the tissues and hence influence the performance and pharmacological activity of the compound as a drug.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/adme] Sometimes liberation and/or toxicity are also considered, yielding LADME, ADMET, or LADMET.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/adme] For a compound to reach a tissue, it usually must be taken into the bloodstream – often via mucous surfaces like the digestive tract (intestinal absorption) – before being taken up by the target cells.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/adme] Factors such as poor compound solubility, gastric emptying time, intestinal transit time, chemical instability in the stomach, and inability to permeate the intestinal wall can all reduce the extent to which a drug is absorbed after oral administration.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/adme] Absorption critically determines the compound's bioavailability.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/adme] Drugs that absorb poorly when taken orally must be administered in some less desirable way, like intravenously or by inhalation (e.g. zanamivir).
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/adme] Routes of administration are an important consideration.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/adme] The compound needs to be carried to its effector site, most often via the bloodstream.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/adme] From there, the compound may distribute into muscle and organs, usually to differing extents.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/adme] After entry into the systemic circulation, either by intravascular injection or by absorption from any of the various extracellular sites, the drug is subjected to numerous distribution processes that tend to lower its plasma concentration.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/adme] Distribution is defined as the reversible transfer of a drug between one compartment to another.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/adme] Some factors affecting drug distribution include regional blood flow rates, molecular size, polarity and binding to serum proteins, forming a complex.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/adme] Distribution can be a serious problem at some natural barriers like the blood–brain barrier.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/adme] Compounds begin to break down as soon as they enter the body.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/adme] The majority of small-molecule drug metabolism is carried out in the liver by redox enzymes, termed cytochrome P450 enzymes.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/adme] As metabolism occurs, the initial (parent) compound is converted to new compounds called metabolites.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/adme] When metabolites are pharmacologically inert, metabolism deactivates the administered dose of parent drug and this usually reduces the effects on the body.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/adme] Metabolites may also be pharmacologically active, sometimes more so than the parent drug (see prodrug).
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/adme] Compounds and their metabolites need to be removed from the body via excretion, usually through the kidneys (urine) or in the feces.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/adme] Unless excretion is complete, accumulation of foreign substances can adversely affect normal metabolism.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/adme] There are three main sites where drug excretion occurs.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/adme] The kidney is the most important site and it is where products are excreted through urine.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/adme] Biliary excretion or fecal excretion is the process that initiates in the liver and passes through to the gut until the products are finally excreted along with waste products or feces.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/adme] The last main method of excretion is through the lungs (e.g. anesthetic gases).
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/adme] Sometimes, the potential or real toxicity of the compound is taken into account (**ADME-Tox** or **ADMET**).
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/adme] Parameters used to characterize toxicity include the median lethal dose (LD50) and therapeutic index.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/adme] Computational chemists try to predict the ADME-Tox qualities of compounds through methods like QSPR or QSAR.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/adme] The route of administration critically influences ADME.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/amr-r-package] It has aimed to provide a standard for clean and reproducible AMR data analysis, enabling surveillance and treatment evaluation in both clinical and research settings.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/amr-r-package] Since its first public release on CRAN in early 2018, the package has been downloaded from over 175 countries, as measured by CRAN download logs.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/amr-r-package] It has been adopted in clinical, veterinary, and environmental microbiology settings worldwide.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/amr-r-package] The package was initially developed at the University of Groningen and the University Medical Center Groningen (UMCG), in the Netherlands.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/amr-r-package] The work was published as a peer-reviewed paper in the *Journal of Statistical Software* and formed the basis of two PhD theses at the University of Groningen.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/amr-r-package] According to CRAN, the package has no external dependencies and is compatible with R versions from R-3.0 (April 2013) onwards.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/amr-r-package] Antimicrobial resistance is recognised by the World Health Organization as one of the leading public health threats globally.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/amr-r-package] Laboratories routinely test microorganisms for resistance against antimicrobial agents, and the resulting data must be reported and analysed at various levels, from local hospitals to international surveillance networks.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/amr-r-package] Despite the existence of international standards for testing and reporting, there was, prior to the AMR package, a lack of standardised open-source tools to process and analyse these data in a reproducible manner.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/amr-r-package] Data from laboratory information systems often require substantial cleaning and validation before analysis, and meaningful interpretation depends on up-to-date reference data, such as microbial taxonomy and clinical breakpoint guidelines.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/amr-r-package] The AMR package was developed to bridge this gap, providing an integrated toolbox that incorporates relevant international guidelines and reference data directly into the analysis workflow.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/amr-r-package] The package offers tools for several core tasks in AMR data analysis.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/amr-r-package] A comprehensive data set of antimicrobial and antiviral agents is included, linked to international coding systems such as the ATC classification, EARS-Net, PubChem, LOINC, and SNOMED CT.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/amr-r-package] These enable the interpretation of raw laboratory measurements, such as minimum inhibitory concentration values and disk diffusion diameters, into standardised susceptibility categories.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/amr-r-package] Additional functions support the determination of first isolates per patient, the generation of antibiograms (including WISCA), the identification of multi-drug resistant organisms, and the calculation and visualisation of resistance proportions.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/amr-r-package] The package can import data in any format, including exports from the WHO's WHONET software.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/amr-r-package] All reference data sets are freely available for download in multiple formats, including Microsoft Excel, Apache Parquet, SPSS, Stata, and plain text, making them accessible to users outside the R ecosystem as well.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/amr-r-package] AMR introduces several new data types (called S3 classes) to R, including `mo` (microorganism codes), `ab` (antimicrobial drug codes), `sir` (susceptibility interpretation results), `mic` (minimum inhibitory concentrations), and `disk` (disk diffusion diameters).
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/amr-r-package] These classes support validation, intelligent coercion, and integration with common R workflows.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/amr-r-package] A Python wrapper is also available, which runs the AMR R package natively in Python.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/amr-r-package] The Python package follows the same version numbering and is built automatically alongside the R package.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/amr-r-package] The AMR package is licensed under the GNU General Public License v2.0 (GPL-2).
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Antibiotic resistance is a serious result of AMR.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Resistance arises through spontaneous mutation, horizontal gene transfer, and increased selective pressure from antibiotic overuse, both in medicine and agriculture, which accelerates resistance development.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Preventive measures, such as using narrow-spectrum antibiotics and improving hygiene practices, aim to reduce the spread of resistance.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] The World Health Organization (WHO) claims that AMR is one of the top global public health and development threats, estimating that bacterial AMR was directly responsible for 1.27 million global deaths in 2019 and contributed to 4.95 million deaths.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] The burden of AMR is immense, with nearly 5 million annual deaths associated with resistant infections.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Infections from AMR microbes are more challenging to treat and often require costly alternative therapies that may have more severe side effects.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Moreover, the WHO and other international bodies warn that AMR could lead to up to 10 million deaths annually by 2050 unless actions are taken.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Global initiatives, such as calls for international AMR treaties, emphasize coordinated efforts to limit misuse, fund research, and provide access to necessary antimicrobials in developing nations.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] However, the COVID-19 pandemic redirected resources and scientific attention away from AMR, intensifying the challenge.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Antimicrobial resistance means that a microorganism is resistant to an antimicrobial drug that was once able to treat an infection by that microorganism.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Resistance is a property of the microbe, not a person or other organism infected by a microbe.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] All types of microbes can develop drug resistance.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Thus, there are antibiotic, antifungal, antiviral and antiparasitic resistance.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Antibiotic resistance is a subset of antimicrobial resistance.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] This more specific resistance is linked to bacteria and thus broken down into two further subsets, microbiological and clinical.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Microbiological resistance is the most common and occurs from genes, mutated or inherited, that allow the bacteria to resist the mechanism to kill the microbe associated with certain antibiotics.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Clinical resistance is shown through the failure of many therapeutic techniques where the bacteria that are normally susceptible to a treatment become resistant after surviving the outcome of the treatment.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] In both cases of acquired resistance, the bacteria can pass the genetic catalyst for resistance through horizontal gene transfer: conjugation, transduction, or transformation.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] This allows the resistance to spread across the same species of pathogen or even similar bacterial pathogens.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] WHO report released April 2014 stated, "this serious threat is no longer a prediction for the future, it is happening right now in every region of the world and has the potential to affect anyone, of any age, in any country.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] In 2024, nearly 5 million deaths were associated with AMR and deaths attributable to AMR numbered 1.27 million.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] One in five people who died due to AMR were children under five years old.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] In 2018, WHO considered antibiotic resistance to be one of the biggest threats to global health, food security and development.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control calculated that in 2015 there were 671,689 infections in the EU and European Economic Area caused by antibiotic-resistant bacteria, resulting in 33,110 deaths.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Most were acquired in healthcare settings.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] In 2019 there were 133,000 deaths caused by AMR.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] AMR is driven largely by the misuse and overuse of antimicrobials.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] They reproduce and spread quickly, and they also can adapt to their environment and change how well they can survive.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Yet, at the same time, many people do not have access to essential antimicrobials.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] This leads to microbes either evolving a defense against drugs used to treat them, or certain strains of microbes that have a natural resistance to antimicrobials becoming much more prevalent than the ones that are easily defeated with medication.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Genetic changes can also occur, which would allow the microbe to survive.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] While antimicrobial resistance does occur naturally over time, the use of antimicrobial agents in a variety of settings both within the healthcare industry and outside of has led to antimicrobial resistance becoming increasingly more prevalent.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Although many microbes develop resistance to antibiotics over time through natural mutation, overprescribing and inappropriate prescription of antibiotics have accelerated the problem.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] During mutation, when replication happens, these mutations help individual microbes survive exposure.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] (NIAID, 2025) It is possible that as many as 1 in 3 prescriptions written for antibiotics are unnecessary.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Every year, approximately 154 million prescriptions for antibiotics are written.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Of these, up to 46 million are unnecessary or inappropriate for the condition that the patient has.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Microbes may naturally develop resistance through genetic mutations that occur during cell division, and although random mutations are rare, many microbes reproduce frequently and rapidly, increasing the chances of members of the population acquiring a mutation that increases resistance.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] In contrast to that, recent research suggests that, contrary to the traditional model of rapid genetic mutation, mycobacteria maintain high genomic stability under antibiotic pressure, relying instead on phenotypic tolerance and DNA-repair mechanisms for survival.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Many individuals stop taking antibiotics when they begin to feel better.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] When this occurs, it is possible that the microbes that are less susceptible to treatment still remain in the body.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] If these microbes are able to continue to reproduce, this can lead to an infection by bacteria that are less susceptible or even resistant to an antibiotic.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Microbes may also get genes from each other, which makes them drug-resistant.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Bacteria that have drug-resistant DNA often transfer a copy of these genes to the other bacteria.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] This process, known as horizontal gene transfer, allows resistance genes to spread rapidly between different bacterial species through mechanisms such as conjugation, transformation, and transduction.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Bacteria become resistant to antibiotics by changing themselves or acquiring resistance genes from other bacteria.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Over the past 20 years, antimicrobial resistance (AMR) has grown, making common infections like respiratory infections, urinary tract infections, STDs, and tuberculosis harder to treat.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] New antibiotics are not being developed fast enough and may lead to a "post-antibiotic era" where some infections are untreatable.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] AMR makes infections more difficult and costly to treat.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Proper antibiotic use—correct drug, dose, and duration—and strict hospital hygiene are essential.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Combating AMR requires cooperation among governments, healthcare workers, researchers, pharmaceutical companies, farmers, and the public through responsible antibiotic use, monitoring resistance, limiting antibiotics in animals, and improving access to medicines, vaccines, and tests.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Prevention is the most effective strategy.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Along with careful antibiotic use, there is a need for new drugs, alternative treatments, better diagnostics, and vaccines.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Without coordinated global action, vital medical procedures like surgery, organ transplants, neonatal care, and cancer treatment could be at risk.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Antimicrobial resistance can evolve naturally due to continued exposure to antimicrobials.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Natural selection means that organisms that are able to adapt to their environment, survive, and continue to produce offspring.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] As a result, the types of microorganisms that are able to survive over time with continued attack by certain antimicrobial agents will naturally become more prevalent in the environment, and those without this resistance will become obsolete.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Some contemporary antimicrobial resistances have also evolved naturally before the use of antimicrobials of human clinical uses.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] For instance, methicillin-resistance evolved as a pathogen of hedgehogs, possibly as a co-evolutionary adaptation of the pathogen to hedgehogs that are infected by a dermatophyte that naturally produces antibiotics.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Also, many soil fungi and bacteria are natural competitors and the original antibiotic penicillin discovered by Alexander Fleming rapidly lost clinical effectiveness in treating humans and, furthermore, none of the other natural penicillins (F, K, N, X, O, U1 or U6) are currently in clinical use.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Antimicrobial resistance can be acquired from other microbes through swapping genes in a process termed horizontal gene transfer.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] This means that once a gene for resistance to an antibiotic appears in a microbial community, it can then spread to other microbes, potentially moving from a non-disease causing microbe to a disease-causing microbe.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] This process is heavily driven by the natural selection processes that happen during antibiotic use or misuse.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Over time, most of the strains of bacteria and infections present will be the type resistant to the antimicrobial agent being used to treat them, making this agent now ineffective to defeat most microbes.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] With the increased use of antimicrobial agents, there is a speeding up of this natural process.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] In the vast majority of countries, antibiotics can only be prescribed by a doctor and supplied by a pharmacy.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Self-medication by consumers is defined as "the taking of medicines on one's own initiative or on another person's suggestion, who is not a certified medical professional", and it has been identified as one of the primary reasons for the evolution of antimicrobial resistance.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Self-medication with antibiotics is an unsuitable way of using them but a common practice in resource-constrained countries.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] The practice exposes individuals to the risk of bacteria that have developed antimicrobial resistance.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Many people resort to this out of necessity, when access to a physician is unavailable, or when patients have a limited amount of time or money to see a doctor.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] This increased access makes it extremely easy to obtain antimicrobials.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] An example is India, where in the state of Punjab 73% of the population resorted to treating their minor health issues and chronic illnesses through self-medication.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Self-medication is higher outside the hospital environment.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] The prevalence of self-medication in low- and middle-income countries (LMICs) ranges from 8.1% to 93%.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Accessibility, affordability, and conditions of health facilities, as well as the health-seeking behavior, are factors that influence self-medication in low- and middle-income countries.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] To determine the public's knowledge and preconceived notions on antibiotic resistance, a screening of 3,537 articles published in Europe, Asia, and North America was done.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Of the 55,225 total people surveyed in the articles, 70% had heard of antibiotic resistance previously, but 88% of those people thought it referred to some type of physical change in the human body.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Clinical misuse by healthcare professionals is another contributor to increased antimicrobial resistance.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Studies done in the US show that the indication for treatment of antibiotics, choice of the agent used, and the duration of therapy was incorrect in up to 50% of the cases studied.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] In 2010 and 2011 about a third of antibiotic prescriptions in outpatient settings in the United States were not necessary.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Another study in an intensive care unit in a major hospital in France has shown that 30% to 60% of prescribed antibiotics were unnecessary.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] These inappropriate uses of antimicrobial agents promote the evolution of antimicrobial resistance by supporting the bacteria in developing genetic alterations that lead to resistance.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] This demonstrates that many doctors underestimate the impact that their own prescribing habits have on antimicrobial resistance as a whole.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] It also confirms that some physicians may be overly cautious and prescribe antibiotics for both medical or legal reasons, even when clinical indications for use of these medications are not always confirmed.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] This can lead to unnecessary antimicrobial use, a pattern which may have worsened during the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Studies have shown that common misconceptions about the effectiveness and necessity of antibiotics to treat common mild illnesses contribute to their overuse.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Important to the conversation of antibiotic use is the veterinary medical system.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Veterinary oversight is required by law for all medically important antibiotics.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Veterinarians use the Pharmacokinetic/pharmacodynamic model (PK/PD) approach to ensuring that the correct dose of the drug is delivered to the correct place at the correct timing.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Increased antibiotic use during the early waves of the COVID-19 pandemic may exacerbate this global health challenge.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Moreover, pandemic burdens on some healthcare systems may contribute to antibiotic-resistant infections.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] The use of disinfectants such as alcohol-based hand sanitizers, and antiseptic hand wash may also have the potential to increase antimicrobial resistance.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Overuse of disinfectants can lead to mutations that induce antimicrobial resistance.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] On the other hand, "increased hand hygiene, decreased international travel, and decreased elective hospital procedures may have reduced AMR pathogen selection and spread in the short term" during the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Critically ill patients are prone to infections, and because of that, they often require antimicrobials.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] The more antimicrobials, the more resistance one becomes to it.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Antimicrobial resistance (AMR) significantly strains healthcare systems and national economies.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] The World Bank estimates that by 2050, AMR could increase healthcare costs by around US$1 trillion and cause global economic losses of US$1–3.4 trillion annually by 2030.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Resistant infections are harder to treat, often requiring longer hospital stays, additional tests, and stronger, more expensive medications, placing extra pressure on hospitals and health systems, especially during pandemics.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] A 2024 United Nations High-Level Meeting on AMR has pledged to reduce deaths associated with bacterial AMR by 10% over the next six years.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] In their first major declaration on the issue since 2016, global leaders also committed to raising $100 million to update and implement AMR action plans.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] However, the final draft of the declaration omitted an earlier target to reduce antibiotic use in animals by 30% by 2030, due to opposition from meat-producing countries and the farming industry.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Critics argue this omission is a major weakness, as livestock accounts for around 73% of global sales of antimicrobial agents, including antibiotics, antivirals, and antiparasitics.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Considering the complex interactions between humans, animals and the environment, it is also important to consider the environmental aspects and contributors to antimicrobial resistance.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] One of these factors is human and hospital waste, which is a substantial contributor to environmental antimicrobial resistance (AMR).
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] It is estimated that around 50–80% of antibiotics are passed unmetabolized in urine and 4–30% in feces, causing large quantities of active antibiotics to enter sewage systems.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Sewage environments contain high levels of antimicrobial-resistant bacteria (ARB), antimicrobial resistance genes (ARGs), and mobile genetic elements such as plasmids, which enable rapid gene exchange.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Wastewater treatment plants (WWTPs) are typically not designed to remove AMR; in some cases, multidrug-resistant species such as *Escherichia, Shigella, and Klebsiella* can increase twofold in treated wastewater.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Methicillin-resistant *Staphylococcus aureus* (MRSA) has also been detected in both raw and treated sewage.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Agriculture is also a major contributor to environmental AMR.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Manure from livestock (such as cattle, sheep, etc.) contains residual antibiotics, which enter the soil as farmers usually use it as fertilizer.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] These are typically at levels of 1–10 mg/kg, and also contain ARBs and ARGs.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] One megaton of antibiotics has been estimated to have entered global soils through manure application.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Pathogens can survive in soil for up to 10 years and on plant surfaces for up to 1 year, thereby enabling long-term environmental continuation of AMR.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Because manure can be applied to diverse crops, residual antibiotics and resistance genes can enter plant tissues and the surrounding soil microbiota, contributing to AMR detected on fruits and vegetables.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Heavy metals in soil, often introduced through fertilizers or industrial processes, can drive cross- and co-resistance mechanisms that select for antibiotic-resistant bacteria even when no antibiotics are present.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Similar selective results happen with biocides and pesticides.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Aquaculture is an underrecognized source of environmental AMR.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Approximately 70% of antibiotics administered in aquaculture enter surrounding waterways, and tetracycline-resistant genes have been found even in isolated environments such as Antarctica and the Arctic.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Antibiotic usage varies substantially across countries, showing the major differences in regulatory oversight.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] High antibiotic use in many Asian aquaculture systems has added to the elevated levels of clinically important resistance genes in sediments and river systems.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Recent research has shown that AMR also occurs through the air.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Airborne resistance genes have been detected at high levels in major urban centers, and farms have been determined as hotspots for airborne AMR, with resistance markers detected in the air surrounding animal operations.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] The antimicrobial resistance crisis also extends to the food industry, specifically with food producing animals.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] With an ever-increasing human population, there is constant pressure to intensify productivity in many agricultural sectors, including the production of meat as a source of protein.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Antibiotics are fed to livestock to act as growth supplements, and a preventive measure to decrease the likelihood of infections.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Farmers typically use antibiotics in animal feed to improve growth rates and prevent infections.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] However, this is illogical as antibiotics are used to treat infections and not prevent infections.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] 80% of antibiotic use in the U.S. is for agricultural purposes and about 70% of these are medically important.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Overusing antibiotics gives the bacteria time to adapt leaving higher doses or even stronger antibiotics needed to combat the infection.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Though antibiotics for growth promotion were banned throughout the EU in 2006, 40 countries still use antibiotics to promote growth.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] This can result in the transfer of resistant bacterial strains into the food that humans eat, causing potentially fatal transfer of disease.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] While the practice of using antibiotics as growth promoters does result in better yields and meat products, it is a major issue and needs to be decreased to prevent antimicrobial resistance.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Though the evidence linking antimicrobial usage in livestock to antimicrobial resistance is limited, the World Health Organization Advisory Group on Integrated Surveillance of Antimicrobial Resistance strongly recommended the reduction of use of medically important antimicrobials in livestock.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Additionally, the Advisory Group stated that such antimicrobials should be expressly prohibited for both growth promotion and disease prevention in food producing animals.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] By mapping antimicrobial consumption in livestock, it was predicted that in 228 countries there would be a total 67% increase in consumption of antibiotics by livestock by 2030.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] In some countries such as Brazil, Russia, India, China, and South Africa it is predicted that a 99% increase will occur.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Several countries have restricted the use of antibiotics in livestock, including Canada, China, Japan, and the US.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] These restrictions are sometimes associated with a reduction of the prevalence of antimicrobial resistance in humans.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Most pesticides protect crops against insects and plants, but in some cases antimicrobial pesticides are used to protect against various microorganisms such as bacteria, viruses, fungi, algae, and protozoa.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] The overuse of many pesticides in an effort to have a higher yield of crops has resulted in many of these microbes evolving a tolerance against these antimicrobial agents.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Currently there are over 4000 antimicrobial pesticides registered with the US Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) and sold to market, showing the widespread use of these agents.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] It is estimated that for every single meal a person consumes, 0.3 g of pesticides is used, as 90% of all pesticide use is in agriculture.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] A majority of these products are used to help defend against the spread of infectious diseases, and hopefully protect public health.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] But out of the large amount of pesticides used, it is also estimated that less than 0.1% of those antimicrobial agents, actually reach their targets.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] That leaves over 99% of all pesticides used available to contaminate other resources.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] In soil, air, and water these antimicrobial agents are able to spread, coming in contact with more microorganisms and leading to these microbes evolving mechanisms to tolerate and further resist pesticides.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] The use of antifungal azole pesticides that drive environmental azole resistance have been linked to azole resistance cases in the clinical setting.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] The same issues confront the novel antifungal classes (e.g. orotomides) which are again being used in both the clinic and agriculture.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Wildlife, including wild and migratory birds, serve as indicators of ecosystem health.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] They act as a reservoir for zoonotic diseases and antimicrobial-resistant organisms.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Birds are a key link between the transmission of zoonotic diseases to human populations.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] By the same token, increased contact between wild birds and human populations (including domesticated animals), has increased the amount of anti-microbial resistance (AMR) to the bird population.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] The introduction of AMR to wild birds positively correlates with human pollution and increased human contact.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Additionally, wild birds can participate in horizontal gene transfer with bacteria, leading to the transmission of antibiotic-resistant genes (ARG).
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] For simplicity, wild bird populations can be divided into two major categories, wild sedentary birds and wild migrating birds.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Wild sedentary bird exposure to AMR is through increased contact with densely populated areas, human waste, domestic animals, and domestic animal/livestock waste.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Especially if they are predators, wild, sedentary birds can come into contact with prey that interact more closely with humans.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Wild migrating birds interact with sedentary birds in different environments along their migration route.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] This increases the rate and diversity of AMR across varying ecosystems.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Neglect of wildlife in the global discussions surrounding health security and AMR, creates large barriers to true AMR surveillance.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] The surveillance of antimicrobial-resistant resistant organisms in wild birds is a potential metric for the rate of AMR in the environment.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] This surveillance also allows for further investigation into the transmission routes between different ecosystems and human populations (including domesticated animals and livestock).
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Such information gathered from wild bird biomes, can help identify patterns of diseased transmission and better target interventions.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] These targeted interventions can inform the use of antimicrobial agents and reduce the persistence of multidrug resistant organisms.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Recent studies demonstrate the importance of wild birds as sentinels for AMR.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] For example, *Escherichia coli* isolated from free-ranging Bonelli's eagles (*Aquila fasciata*) in eastern Spain showed that 53.3% of isolates were resistant to at least one antimicrobial, and 29.3% were multidrug-resistant, despite the species' minimal exposure to human-associated environments.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] The study also reported resistance to colistin and meropenem, two last-resort antibiotics, and documented 19 different multidrug-resistance patterns, suggesting persistent and heterogeneous selective pressures in the environment.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Because Bonelli's eagles live far from humans and urban areas, they acquire resistance largely through interactions with prey species that interact with humans.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] These findings demonstrate how AMR can spread into remote ecosystems via indirect pathways, strengthening the role of wild birds, particularly apex predators, as effective bioindicators in AMR surveillance.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Permafrost is a term used to refer to any ground that remained frozen for two years or more, with the oldest known examples continuously frozen for around 700,000 years.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] In the recent decades, permafrost has been rapidly thawing due to climate change.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] The cold preserves any organic matter inside the permafrost, and it is possible for microorganisms to resume their life functions once it thaws.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] While some common pathogens such as influenza, smallpox or the bacteria associated with pneumonia have failed to survive intentional attempts to revive them, more cold-adapted microorganisms such as anthrax, or several ancient plant and amoeba viruses, have successfully survived prolonged thaw.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Some scientists have argued that the inability of known causative agents of contagious diseases to survive being frozen and thawed makes this threat unlikely.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Instead, there have been suggestions that when modern pathogenic bacteria interact with the ancient ones, they may, through horizontal gene transfer, pick up genetic sequences which are associated with antimicrobial resistance, exacerbating an already difficult issue.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Antibiotics to which permafrost bacteria have displayed at least some resistance include chloramphenicol, streptomycin, kanamycin, gentamicin, tetracycline, spectinomycin and neomycin.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] However, other studies show that resistance levels in ancient bacteria to modern antibiotics remain lower than in the contemporary bacteria from the active layer of thawed ground above them, which may mean that this risk is "no greater" than from any other soil.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] There have been increasing public calls for global collective action to address the threat, including a proposal for an international treaty on antimicrobial resistance.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Further detail and attention is still needed to recognize and measure trends in resistance on the international level; the idea of a global tracking system has been suggested but implementation has yet to occur.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] A system of this nature would provide insight to areas of high resistance as well as information necessary for evaluating programs, introducing interventions and other changes made to fight or reverse antibiotic resistance.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Antimicrobial resistance (AMR) is commonly described within a *One Health* framework, which emphasizes the interconnected relationships between human health, animal health, and the environment.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Antimicrobial use in clinical medicine, veterinary practice, and agriculture has been associated with the selection and spread of resistant microorganisms across these sectors.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Research indicates that resistant bacteria and antimicrobial resistance genes can move between humans, animals, and environmental reservoirs through multiple pathways, including food production systems, direct contact, and exposure to contaminated water or soil.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] These pathways contribute to the persistence and wider dissemination of antimicrobial resistance beyond individual settings.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Environmental sources have been increasingly examined in relation to AMR.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Wastewater systems, agricultural runoff, and pharmaceutical residues have been identified as potential reservoirs where resistant microorganisms and resistance genes may persist.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Such reservoirs may facilitate ongoing transmission between environmental, animal, and human populations.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Efforts to address AMR within a One Health framework typically involve coordinated strategies across sectors, including antimicrobial stewardship, infection prevention and control, and improvements in sanitation and hygiene.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Evidence from systematic reviews suggests that interventions such as farm biosecurity and water, sanitation, and hygiene (WASH) practices may reduce antimicrobial use and contribute to limiting the development and spread of resistance.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Delaying or minimizing the use of antibiotics for certain conditions may help safely reduce their use.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Antimicrobial treatment duration should be based on the infection and other health problems a person may have.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] For many infections once a person has improved there is little evidence that stopping treatment causes more resistance.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Some, therefore, feel that stopping early may be reasonable in some cases.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Other infections, however, do require long courses regardless of whether a person feels better.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Delaying antibiotics for ailments such as a sore throat and otitis media may have no difference in the rate of complications compared with immediate antibiotics, for example.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] When treating respiratory tract infections, clinical judgement is required as to the appropriate treatment (delayed or immediate antibiotic use).
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] ResistanceOpen is an online global map of antimicrobial resistance developed by HealthMap which displays aggregated data on antimicrobial resistance from publicly available and user submitted data.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The website can display data for a 25 miles (40 km) radius from a location.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Users may submit data from antibiograms for individual hospitals or laboratories.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] European data is from the EARS-Net (European Antimicrobial Resistance Surveillance Network), part of the ECDC.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] ResistanceMap is a website by the Center for Disease Dynamics, Economics & Policy and provides data on antimicrobial resistance on a global level.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The WHO's AMR global action plan also recommends antimicrobial resistance surveillance in animals.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Initial steps in the EU for establishing the veterinary counterpart EARS-Vet (EARS-Net for veterinary medicine) have been made.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] AMR data from pets in particular is scarce, but needed to support antibiotic stewardship in veterinary medicine.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] By comparison there is a lack of national and international monitoring programs for antifungal resistance.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Antimicrobial stewardship programmes appear useful in reducing rates of antimicrobial resistance.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The antimicrobial stewardship program will also provide pharmacists with the knowledge to educate patients that antibiotics will not work for a virus for example.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Excessive antimicrobial use has become one of the top contributors to the evolution of antimicrobial resistance.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Since the beginning of the antimicrobial era, antimicrobials have been used to treat a wide range of infectious diseases.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Overuse of antimicrobials has become the primary cause of rising levels of antimicrobial resistance.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Prescribers are willing to prescribe antimicrobials to individuals who believe that antimicrobials can cure nearly all illnesses, including viral infections like the common cold.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] In an analysis of drug prescriptions, 36% of individuals with a cold or an upper respiratory infection (both usually viral in origin) were given prescriptions for antibiotics.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] These prescriptions increase the risk of further evolution of antibiotic resistant bacteria.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Using antimicrobials without prescription is another driving force leading to the overuse of antibiotics to self-treat diseases like the common cold, cough, fever, and dysentery resulting in an epidemic of antibiotic resistance in countries like Bangladesh, risking its spread around the globe.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Introducing strict antibiotic stewardship in the outpatient setting to reduce inappropriate prescribing of antibiotics may reduce the emerging bacterial resistance.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The WHO AWaRe (Access, Watch, Reserve) guidance and antibiotic book has been introduced to guide antibiotic choice for the 30 most common infections in adults and children to reduce inappropriate prescribing in primary care and hospitals.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Narrow-spectrum antibiotics are preferred due to their lower resistance potential, and broad-spectrum antibiotics are only recommended for people with more severe symptoms.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Some antibiotics are more likely to confer resistance, so are kept as reserve antibiotics in the AWaRe book.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Various diagnostic strategies have been employed to prevent the overuse of antifungal therapy in the clinic, proving a safe alternative to empirical antifungal therapy, and thus underpinning antifungal stewardship schemes.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Antimicrobial stewardship teams in hospitals are encouraging optimal use of antimicrobials.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The goals of antimicrobial stewardship are to help practitioners pick the right drug at the right dose and duration of therapy while preventing misuse and minimizing the development of resistance.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Stewardship interventions may reduce the length of stay by an average of slightly over 1 day while not increasing the risk of death.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Dispensing the exact number of antibiotic pharmaceutical units necessary to complete an ongoing treatment can reduce excess antibiotics.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] A 2025 cross-sectional study of 125 pharmacists at a UK NHS Foundation Trust examined knowledge, attitudes, and perceptions regarding antimicrobial stewardship following the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The study found that more than 85% of pharmacists recognized antimicrobial resistance as a public health concern.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] However, the pandemic created challenges, with 80% reporting that COVID-19 patient conditions influenced antibiotic prescription.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] A 2026 systematic review of 73 studies examined arthropod-mediated pathogen transmission in hospitals.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Research indicates that cockroaches, flies, and ants frequently harbor multidrug-resistant bacteria, fungi, and viruses.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] While direct causality is difficult to prove, genetic evidence links these pests to hospital-associated infections.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Given the volume of care provided in primary care (general practice), recent strategies have focused on reducing unnecessary antimicrobial prescribing in this setting.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Simple interventions, such as written information explaining when taking antibiotics is not necessary, for example in common infections of the upper respiratory tract, have been shown to reduce antibiotic prescribing.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Various tools are also available to help professionals decide if prescribing antimicrobials is necessary.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Parental expectations, driven by the worry for their children's health, can influence how often children are prescribed antibiotics.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Parents often rely on their clinician for advice and reassurance.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] However a lack of plain language information and not having adequate time for consultation negatively impacts this relationship.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] In effect parents often rely on past experiences in their expectations rather than reassurance from the clinician.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Adequate time for consultation and plain language information can help parents make informed decisions and avoid unnecessary antibiotic use.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The prescriber should closely adhere to the five rights of drug administration: the right patient, the right drug, the right dose, the right route, and the right time.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Microbiological samples should be taken for culture and sensitivity testing before treatment when indicated and treatment potentially changed based on the susceptibility report.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Health workers and pharmacists can help tackle antibiotic resistance by: enhancing infection prevention and control; only prescribing and dispensing antibiotics when they are truly needed; prescribing and dispensing the right antibiotic(s) to treat the illness.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] A unit dose system implemented in community pharmacies can also reduce antibiotic leftovers at households.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Despite these, written guideline intervention for prescriber to do history taking and provision of advice and knowledge of pharmacists and non‐pharmacists may not reduce the sales of non‐prescription antimicrobial drugs in community pharmacies, drugstores, and other medicine outlets.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] People can help tackle resistance by using antibiotics only when prescribed for a bacterial infetion as well as completing the full treatment course, never sharing medication with others, and using proper disposal methods for excess drugs.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Basic hygiene practices also help prevent the spread of bacteria.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] • Germany and Sweden also have lower prescribing rates, with Sweden's rate having been declining since 2007. • Greece, France and Belgium have high prescribing rates.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Infectious disease control through improved water, sanitation and hygiene (WASH) infrastructure needs to be included in the antimicrobial resistance (AMR) agenda.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Growing usage of antibiotics together with persistent infectious disease levels have led to a dangerous cycle in which reliance on antimicrobials increases while the efficacy of drugs diminishes.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The proper use of infrastructure for water, sanitation and hygiene (WASH) can result in a 47–72 percent decrease of diarrhea cases treated with antibiotics depending on the type of intervention and its effectiveness.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] A reduction of the diarrhea disease burden through improved infrastructure would result in large decreases in the number of diarrhea cases treated with antibiotics.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] This was estimated as ranging from 5 million in Brazil to up to 590 million in India by the year 2030.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The strong link between increased consumption and resistance indicates that this will directly mitigate the accelerating spread of AMR.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Sanitation and water for all by 2030 is Goal Number 6 of the Sustainable Development Goals.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] An increase in hand washing compliance by hospital staff results in decreased rates of resistant organisms.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Water supply and sanitation infrastructure in health facilities offer opportunities for combatting AMR, and investment should be increased.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] There is much room for improvement: WHO and UNICEF estimated in 2015 that 38% of health facilities did not have a source of water, nearly 19% had no toilets and 35% had no water and soap or alcohol-based hand rub for handwashing.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Manufacturers of antimicrobials need to improve the treatment of their wastewater (by using industrial wastewater treatment processes) to reduce the release of residues into the environment.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] It is established that the use of antibiotics in animal husbandry can give rise to AMR resistances in bacteria found in food animals to the antibiotics being administered (through injections or medicated feeds).
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] For this reason only antimicrobials that are deemed "not-clinically relevant" are used in these practices.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Unlike resistance to antibacterials, antifungal resistance can be driven by arable farming, currently there is no regulation on the use of similar antifungal classes in agriculture and the clinic.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Recent studies have shown that the prophylactic use of "non-priority" or "non-clinically relevant" antimicrobials in feeds can potentially, under certain conditions, lead to co-selection of environmental AMR bacteria with resistance to medically important antibiotics.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The possibility for co-selection of AMR resistances in the food chain pipeline may have far-reaching implications for human health.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] In 1997, European Union health ministers voted to ban avoparcin and four additional antibiotics used to promote animal growth in 1999.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] In 2006 a ban on the use of antibiotics in European feed, with the exception of two antibiotics in poultry feeds, became effective.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] In Scandinavia, there is evidence that the ban has led to a lower prevalence of antibiotic resistance in (nonhazardous) animal bacterial populations.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] As of 2004, several European countries established a decline of antimicrobial resistance in humans through limiting the use of antimicrobials in agriculture and food industries without jeopardizing animal health or economic cost.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The United States Department of Agriculture (USDA) and the Food and Drug Administration (FDA) collect data on antibiotic use in humans and in a more limited fashion in animals.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] About 80% of antibiotic use in the U.S. is for agriculture purposes, and about 70% of these are medically important.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] This gives reason for concern about the antibiotic resistance crisis in the U.S. and more reason to monitor it.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The FDA first determined in 1977 that there is evidence of emergence of antibiotic-resistant bacterial strains in livestock.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The long-established practice of permitting OTC sales of antibiotics (including penicillin and other drugs) to lay animal owners for administration to their own animals nonetheless continued in all states.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] In 2000, the FDA announced their intention to revoke approval of fluoroquinolone use in poultry production because of substantial evidence linking it to the emergence of fluoroquinolone-resistant *Campylobacter* infections in humans.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Legal challenges from the food animal and pharmaceutical industries delayed the final decision to do so until 2006.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Fluroquinolones have been banned from extra-label use in food animals in the USA since 2007.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] However, they are still used in treatment of companion and exotic animals.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The increasing interconnectedness of the world and the fact that new classes of antibiotics have not been developed and approved for 25 years highlight the extent to which antimicrobial resistance is a global health challenge.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] A global action plan to tackle the growing problem of resistance to antibiotics and other antimicrobial medicines was endorsed at the Sixty-eighth World Health Assembly in May 2015.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] One of the key objectives of the plan is to improve awareness and understanding of antimicrobial resistance through effective communication, education and training.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] This global action plan developed by the World Health Organization was created to combat the issue of antimicrobial resistance and was guided by the advice of countries and key stakeholders.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The WHO's global action plan is composed of five key objectives that can be targeted through different means, and represents countries coming together to solve a major problem that can have future health consequences.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The World Health Organization has promoted the first World Antibiotic Awareness Week running from 16 to 22 November 2015.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The aim of the week is to increase global awareness of antibiotic resistance.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] It also wants to promote the correct usage of antibiotics across all fields to prevent further instances of antibiotic resistance.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] World Antibiotic Awareness Week has been held every November since 2015.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] For 2017, the Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations (FAO), the World Health Organization (WHO) and the World Organisation for Animal Health (OIE) are together calling for responsible use of antibiotics in humans and animals to reduce the emergence of antibiotic resistance.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] In 2016 the Secretary-General of the United Nations convened the Interagency Coordination Group (IACG) on Antimicrobial Resistance.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The IACG worked with international organizations and experts in human, animal, and plant health to create a plan to fight antimicrobial resistance.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Their report released in April 2019 focuses on the seriousness of antimicrobial resistance and the threat it poses to world health.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] It suggests five recommendations for member states to follow to tackle this increasing threat.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The **One Health** approach recognizes that human, animal, and environmental health are interconnected in the development and spread of antimicrobial resistance (AMR).
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Alteration of target- or binding site: for example, alteration of PBP—the binding target site of penicillins—in MRSA and other penicillin-resistant bacteria.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Another protective mechanism found among bacterial species is ribosomal protection proteins.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] These proteins protect the bacterial cell from antibiotics that target the cell's ribosomes to inhibit protein synthesis.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The mechanism involves the binding of the ribosomal protection proteins to the ribosomes of the bacterial cell, which in turn changes its conformational shape.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] This allows the ribosomes to continue synthesizing proteins essential to the cell while preventing antibiotics from binding to the ribosome to inhibit protein synthesis.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Reduced drug accumulation: by decreasing drug permeability or increasing active efflux (pumping out) of the drugs across the cell surface.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] These multidrug efflux pumps within the cellular membrane of certain bacterial species are used to pump antibiotics out of the cell before they are able to do any damage.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] They are often activated by a specific substrate associated with an antibiotic, as in fluoroquinolone resistance.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Ribosome splitting and recycling: for example, drug-mediated stalling of the ribosome by lincomycin and erythromycin unstalled by a heat shock protein found in *Listeria monocytogenes*, which is a homologue of HflX from other bacteria.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Liberation of the ribosome from the drug allows further translation and consequent resistance to the drug.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] There are several different types of germs that have developed a resistance over time.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The six pathogens causing most deaths associated with resistance are *Escherichia coli*, *Staphylococcus aureus, Klebsiella pneumoniae, Streptococcus pneumoniae, Acinetobacter baumannii*, and *Pseudomonas aeruginosa*.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] They were responsible for 929,000 deaths attributable to resistance and 3.57 million deaths associated with resistance in 2019.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Penicillinase-producing *Neisseria gonorrhoeae* developed a resistance to penicillin in 1976.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Another example is Azithromycin-resistant *Neisseria gonorrhoeae*, which developed a resistance to azithromycin in 2011.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] In gram-negative bacteria, plasmid-mediated resistance genes produce proteins that can bind to DNA gyrase, protecting it from the action of quinolones.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Finally, mutations at key sites in DNA gyrase or topoisomerase IV can decrease their binding affinity to quinolones, decreasing the drug's effectiveness.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Some bacteria are naturally resistant to certain antibiotics; for example, gram-negative bacteria are resistant to most β-lactam antibiotics due to the presence of β-lactamase.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Antibiotic resistance can also be acquired as a result of either genetic mutation or horizontal gene transfer.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Although mutations are rare, with spontaneous mutations in the pathogen genome occurring at a rate of about 1 in 105 to 1 in 108 per chromosomal replication, Bacteria reproduce at a high rate, lifespans and production of new generations can be on a timescale of mere hours.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] A new (de novo) mutation in a parent cell can quickly become an inherited mutation of widespread prevalence, resulting in the microevolution of a fully resistant colony.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] However, chromosomal mutations also confer a cost of fitness.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] For example, a ribosomal mutation may protect a bacterial cell by changing the binding site of an antibiotic but may result in slower growth rate.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Moreover, some adaptive mutations can propagate not only through inheritance but also through horizontal gene transfer.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The most common mechanism of horizontal gene transfer is the transferring of plasmids carrying antibiotic resistance genes between bacteria of the same or different species via conjugation.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Recent findings show no necessity of large populations of bacteria for the appearance of antibiotic resistance.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Small populations of *Escherichia coli* in an antibiotic gradient can become resistant.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Any heterogeneous environment with respect to nutrient and antibiotic gradients may facilitate antibiotic resistance in small bacterial populations.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Researchers hypothesize that the mechanism of resistance evolution is based on four SNP mutations in the genome of *E. coli* produced by the gradient of antibiotic.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] In one study, which has implications for space microbiology, a non-pathogenic strain *E. coli* MG1655 was exposed to trace levels of the broad spectrum antibiotic chloramphenicol, under simulated microgravity (LSMMG, or Low Shear Modeled Microgravity) over 1000 generations.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Thus, irrespective of where they are used, the use of an antibiotic would likely result in persistent resistance to that antibiotic, as well as cross-resistance to other antimicrobials.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] In recent years, the emergence and spread of β-lactamases called carbapenemases has become a major health crisis.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] One such carbapenemase is New Delhi metallo-beta-lactamase 1 (NDM-1), an enzyme that makes bacteria resistant to a broad range of beta-lactam antibiotics.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The most common bacteria that make this enzyme are gram-negative such as *E. coli* and *Klebsiella pneumoniae*, but the gene for NDM-1 can spread from one strain of bacteria to another by horizontal gene transfer.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Specific antiviral drugs are used to treat some viral infections.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] These drugs prevent viruses from reproducing by inhibiting essential stages of the virus's replication cycle in infected cells.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Antivirals are used to treat HIV, hepatitis B, hepatitis C, influenza, herpes viruses including varicella zoster virus, cytomegalovirus and Epstein–Barr virus.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] With each virus, some strains have become resistant to the administered drugs.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Antiviral drugs typically target key components of viral reproduction; for example, oseltamivir targets influenza neuraminidase,while guanosine analogs inhibit viral DNA polymerase.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Resistance to antivirals is thus acquired through mutations in the genes that encode the protein targets of the drugs.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Resistance to HIV antivirals is problematic, and even multi-drug resistant strains have evolved.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] One source of resistance is that many current HIV drugs, including NRTIs and NNRTIs, target reverse transcriptase; however, HIV-1 reverse transcriptase is highly error prone and thus mutations conferring resistance arise rapidly.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Resistant strains of the HIV virus emerge rapidly if only one antiviral drug is used.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Using three or more drugs together, termed combination therapy, has helped to control this problem, but new drugs are needed because of the continuing emergence of drug-resistant HIV strains.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Infections by fungi are a cause of high morbidity and mortality in immunocompromised persons, such as those with HIV/AIDS, tuberculosis or receiving chemotherapy.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The fungi *Candida*, *Cryptococcus neoformans* and *Aspergillus fumigatus* cause most of these infections and antifungal resistance occurs in all of them.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Multidrug resistance in fungi is increasing because of the widespread use of antifungal drugs to treat infections in immunocompromised individuals and the use of some agricultural antifungals.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Antifungal resistant disease is associated with increased mortality.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Some fungi (for example, *Candida krusei* and fluconazole) exhibit intrinsic resistance to certain antifungal drugs or classes, whereas some species develop antifungal resistance to external pressures.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Antifungal resistance is a One Health concern, driven by multiple extrinsic factors, including overuse of fungicides, clinical antifungals, environmental change and host factors.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] In the USA fluconazole-resistant Candida species and azole resistance in Aspergillus fumigatus have been highlighted as a growing threat.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] 20 species of *Candida* can cause candidiasis infection, the most common of which is *Candida albicans*.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] *Candida* yeasts normally inhabit the skin and mucous membranes without causing infection.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] However, overgrowth of *Candida* can lead to candidiasis.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] *Candida glabrata)* are becoming resistant to first-line and second-line antifungal agents such as echinocandins and azoles.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The emergence of *Candida auris* as a potential human pathogen that sometimes exhibits multi-class antifungal drug resistance is concerning and has been associated with several outbreaks.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The WHO has released a priority fungal pathogen list, including pathogens with antifungal resistance.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The identification of antifungal resistance is undermined by limited classical diagnosis of infection, where a culture is lacking, preventing susceptibility testing.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] National and international surveillance schemes for fungal disease and antifungal resistance are limited, hampering the understanding of the disease burden and associated resistance.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The application of molecular testing to identify genetic markers associating with resistance may improve the identification of antifungal resistance, but the diversity of mutations associated with resistance is increasing across the fungal species causing infection.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] In addition, a number of resistance mechanisms depend on up-regulation of selected genes (for instance reflux pumps) rather than defined mutations that are amenable to molecular detection.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Due to the limited number of antifungals in clinical use and the increasing global incidence of antifungal resistance, using the existing antifungals in combination might be beneficial in some cases but further research is needed.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Similarly, other approaches that might help to combat the emergence of antifungal resistance could rely on the development of host-directed therapies such as immunotherapy or vaccines.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The protozoan parasites that cause the diseases malaria, trypanosomiasis, toxoplasmosis, cryptosporidiosis and leishmaniasis are important human pathogens.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Malarial parasites that are resistant to the drugs that are currently available to infections are common and this has led to increased efforts to develop new drugs.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Resistance to recently developed drugs such as artemisinin has also been reported.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The problem of drug resistance in malaria has driven efforts to develop vaccines.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Trypanosomes are parasitic protozoa that cause African trypanosomiasis and Chagas disease (American trypanosomiasis).
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] There are no vaccines to prevent these infections so drugs such as pentamidine and suramin, benznidazole and nifurtimox are used to treat infections.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] These drugs are effective but infections caused by resistant parasites have been reported.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Leishmaniasis is caused by protozoa and is a public health problem in sub-tropical and tropical countries.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Drug resistance has "become a major concern".
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The preferred treatment for leishmaniasis regionally; liposomal amphotericin B is used in the Mediterranean basin and pentavalent antimonials are more commonly used in Africa, South America, Bangladesh, India, and Nepal.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Resistance to antibiotics in *Leishmania* is a relatively recent phenomena.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The first reported instance of resistance to antimonials was reported in India in the 1980s.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] In 2022, genomic epidemiologists reported results from a global survey of antimicrobial resistance via genomic wastewater-based epidemiology, finding large regional variations, providing maps, and suggesting resistance genes are also passed on between microbial species that are not closely related.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The WHO provides the Global Antimicrobial Resistance and Use Surveillance System (GLASS) reports which summarize annual (e.g.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] 2020's) data on international AMR, also including an interactive dashboard.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Public Health England reported that the total number of antibiotic resistant infections in England rose by 9% from 55,812 in 2017 to 60,788 in 2018, but antibiotic consumption had fallen by 9% from 20.0 to 18.2 defined daily doses per 1,000 inhabitants per day between 2014 and 2018.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention reported that 2.8 million cases of antibiotic resistance have been reported.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] However, in 2019 overall deaths from antibiotic-resistant infections decreased by 18% and deaths in hospitals decreased by 30%.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The COVID pandemic caused a reversal of much of the progress made on attenuating the effects of antibiotic resistance, resulting in more antibiotic use, more resistant infections, and less data on preventive action.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Hospital-onset infections and deaths both increased by 15% in 2020, and significantly higher rates of infections were reported for 4 out of 6 types of healthcare associated infections.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Owing to rampant misuse, over-prescription, and unregulated over-the-counter access to antibiotics, the growth of AMR superbugs has proliferated in India.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Pharmacies surveyed by the Karnataka government revealed that 80% of drugs were being sold without a prescription.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] In 2019, India reported 300,000 deaths because of infections relating to AMR, India also reports the most number of tuberculosis cases resistant to antibiotics.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The 1950s to 1970s represented the golden age of antibiotic discovery, where countless new classes of antibiotics were discovered to treat previously incurable diseases such as tuberculosis and syphilis.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] However, since that time the discovery of new classes of antibiotics has been almost nonexistent, and represents a situation that is especially problematic considering the resiliency of bacteria shown over time and the continued misuse and overuse of antibiotics in treatment.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Already in 1940, in their letter to the editor of Nature journal, Abraham and Chain identified the enzyme penicillinase as responsible for the deactivation of penicillin in penicillin-resistant bacteria.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] This discovery was the first step in understanding the mechanisms of microbial resistance to β-lactam antibiotics.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The phenomenon of antimicrobial resistance caused by overuse of antibiotics was predicted as early as 1945 by Alexander Fleming who said "The time may come when penicillin can be bought by anyone in the shops.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Antimicrobial resistance can lead to epidemics of enormous proportions if preventive actions are not taken.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] In this day and age current antimicrobial resistance leads to longer hospital stays, higher medical costs, and increased mortality.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Since the mid-1980s pharmaceutical companies have invested in medications for cancer or chronic disease that have greater potential to make money and have "de-emphasized or dropped development of antibiotics".
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] On 20 January 2016 at the World Economic Forum, "80 pharmaceutical and diagnostic companies" called for "transformational commercial models" at an international level to spur research and development on antibiotics and on the use of diagnostic tests.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] A number of countries are considering or implementing delinked payment models for new antimicrobials whereby payment is based on value rather than volume of drug sales.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] This offers the opportunity to pay for valuable new drugs even if they are reserved for use in relatively rare drug resistant infections.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Some global health scholars have argued that a global, legal framework is needed to prevent and control antimicrobial resistance.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] For instance, binding global policies could be used to create antimicrobial use standards, regulate antibiotic marketing, and strengthen global surveillance systems.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Ensuring compliance of involved parties is a challenge.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] For the United States 2016 budget, U.S. president Barack Obama proposed to nearly double the amount of federal funding to "combat and prevent" antibiotic resistance to $1.2 billion.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Many international funding agencies like USAID, DFID, Sida and Gates Foundation have pledged money for developing strategies to counter antimicrobial resistance.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] On 27 March 2015, the White House released a plan to address the increasing need for agencies to combat the rise of antibiotic-resistant bacteria.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The Task Force for Combating Antibiotic-Resistant Bacteria developed *The National Action Plan for Combating Antibiotic-Resistant Bacteria* with the intent of providing a roadmap to guide the US in the antibiotic resistance challenge and with hopes of saving many lives.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] This plan outlines steps taken by the Federal government over the next five years needed to prevent and contain outbreaks of antibiotic-resistant infections; maintain the efficacy of antibiotics already on the market; and to help to develop future diagnostics, antibiotics, and vaccines.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The Action Plan was developed around five goals with focuses on strengthening health care, public health veterinary medicine, agriculture, food safety and research, and manufacturing.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] As of 2023, AMR remains a public health threat in the United States.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] According to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention's 2023 Report on Antibiotic Resistance Threats, over 2.8 million antibiotic-resistant infections occur in the U.S. each year, leading to at least 35,000 deaths annually.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Among the most concerning resistant pathogens are Carbapenem-resistant *Enterobacteriaceae* (CRE), Methicillin-resistant *Staphylococcus aureus* (MRSA), and *Clostridioides difficile* (C. diff), all of which continue to be responsible for severe healthcare-associated infections (HAIs).
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The COVID-19 pandemic led to a disruption in healthcare, with an increase in the use of antibiotics during the treatment of viral infections.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] This rise in antibiotic prescribing, coupled with overwhelmed healthcare systems, contributed to a resurgence in AMR during the pandemic years.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] A 2021 CDC report identified a sharp increase in HAIs caused by resistant pathogens in COVID-19 patients, a trend that has persisted into 2023.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Recent data suggest that although antibiotic use has decreased since the pandemic, some resistant pathogens remain prevalent in healthcare settings.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The CDC has also expanded its Get Ahead of Sepsis campaign in 2023, focusing on raising awareness of AMR's role in sepsis and promoting the judicious use of antibiotics in both healthcare and community settings.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] This initiative has reached millions through social media, healthcare facilities, and public health outreach, aiming to educate the public on the importance of preventing infections and reducing antibiotic misuse.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Trump, severe federal funding cuts in 2025 at the National Institutes of Health (NIH) and many other research entities in the United States are expected to impede progress in combating antimicrobial resistance.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Public health experts believe these budget reductions will adversely affect the development of new antibiotics as well as advances in diagnostics and treatment strategies, thus undermining efforts currently underway to address AMR.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The Infectious Diseases Society of America (IDSA) is but one organization that has expressed grave concern regarding the negative consequences of such extreme budget measures on antimicrobial stewardship, and, as a result, on global health security overall.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] According to World Health Organization, policymakers can help tackle resistance by strengthening resistance-tracking and laboratory capacity and by regulating and promoting the appropriate use of medicines.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Policymakers and industry can help tackle resistance by: fostering research and development of new tools and promoting cooperation and information sharing among all stakeholders.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The U.S. government continues to prioritize AMR mitigation through policy and legislation.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] In 2023, the National Action Plan for Combating Antibiotic-Resistant Bacteria (CARB) 2023-2028 was released, outlining strategic objectives for reducing antibiotic-resistant infections, advancing infection prevention, and accelerating research on new antibiotics.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The plan also emphasizes the importance of improving antibiotic stewardship across healthcare, agriculture, and veterinary settings.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Furthermore, the PASTEUR Act (Pioneering Antimicrobial Subscriptions to End Upsurging Resistance) has gained momentum in Congress.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] If passed, the bill would create a subscription-based payment model to incentivize the development of new antimicrobial drugs, while supporting antimicrobial stewardship programs to reduce the misuse of existing antibiotics.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] This legislation is considered a critical step toward addressing the economic barriers to developing new antimicrobials.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Measuring the costs and benefits of strategies to combat AMR is difficult and policies may only have effects in the distant future.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] In other infectious diseases this problem has been addressed by using mathematical models.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] More research is needed to understand how AMR develops and spreads so that mathematical modelling can be used to anticipate the likely effects of different policies.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Distinguishing infections requiring antibiotics from self-limiting ones is clinically challenging.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] To guide appropriate use of antibiotics and prevent the evolution and spread of antimicrobial resistance, diagnostic tests that provide clinicians with timely, actionable results are needed.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Acute fever is a common reason for seeking medical care and a major cause of morbidity and mortality.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Multiple studies have shown that the use of malaria rapid diagnostic tests without reliable tools to distinguish other fever causes has resulted in increased antibiotic use.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Antimicrobial susceptibility testing (AST) can facilitate a precision medicine approach to treatment by helping clinicians to prescribe more effective and targeted antimicrobial therapy.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] At the same time with traditional phenotypic AST it can take 12 to 48 hours to obtain a result due to the time taken for organisms to grow on/in culture media.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Rapid testing, possible from molecular diagnostics innovations, is defined as "being feasible within an 8-h working shift".
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] There are several commercial Food and Drug Administration-approved assays available which can detect AMR genes from a variety of specimen types.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Progress has been slow due to a range of reasons including cost and regulation.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Genotypic AMR characterisation methods are, however, being increasingly used in combination with machine learning algorithms in research to help better predict phenotypic AMR from organism genotype.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Optical techniques such as phase contrast microscopy in combination with single-cell analysis are another powerful method to monitor bacterial growth.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] In 2017, scientists from Uppsala University in Sweden published a method that applies principles of microfluidics and cell tracking, to monitor bacterial response to antibiotics in less than 30 minutes overall manipulation time.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] This invention was awarded the 8M£ Longitude Prize on AMR in 2024.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Recently, this platform has been advanced by coupling microfluidic chip with optical tweezing to isolate bacteria with altered phenotype directly from the analytical matrix.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Rapid diagnostic methods have also been trialled as antimicrobial stewardship interventions to influence the healthcare drivers of AMR.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Serum procalcitonin measurement has been shown to reduce mortality rate, antimicrobial consumption and antimicrobial-related side-effects in patients with respiratory infections, but impact on AMR has not yet been demonstrated.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Similarly, point of care serum testing of the inflammatory biomarker C-reactive protein has been shown to influence antimicrobial prescribing rates in this patient cohort, but further research is required to demonstrate an effect on rates of AMR.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Clinical investigation to rule out bacterial infections are often done for patients with pediatric acute respiratory infections.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Currently it is unclear if rapid viral testing affects antibiotic use in children.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Vaccines are an essential part of the response to reduce AMR as they prevent infections, reduce the use and overuse of antimicrobials, and slow the emergence and spread of drug-resistant pathogens.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Microorganisms usually do not develop resistance to vaccines because vaccines reduce the spread of the infection and target the pathogen in multiple ways in the same host and possibly in different ways between different hosts.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Furthermore, if the use of vaccines increases, there is evidence that antibiotic resistant strains of pathogens will decrease; the need for antibiotics will naturally decrease as vaccines prevent infection before it occurs.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] A 2024 report by WHO finds that vaccines against 24 pathogens could reduce the number of antibiotics needed by 22% or 2.5 billion DDD every year.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] If vaccines could be rolled out against all the evaluated pathogens, they could save a third of the hospital costs associated with AMR.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Vaccinated people have fewer infections and are protected against potential complications from secondary infections that may need antimicrobial medicines or require admission to hospital.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] However, there are well documented cases of vaccine resistance, although these are usually much less of a problem than antimicrobial resistance.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Antistaphylococcal vaccines have shown limited efficacy, because of immunological variation between *Staphylococcus* species, and the limited duration of effectiveness of the antibodies produced.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Development and testing of more effective vaccines is underway.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Two registrational trials have evaluated vaccine candidates in active immunization strategies against *S. aureus* infection.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] In a phase II trial, a bivalent vaccine of capsular proteins 5 & 8 was tested in 1804 hemodialysis patients with a primary fistula or synthetic graft vascular access.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] After 40 weeks following vaccination a protective effect was seen against *S. aureus* bacteremia, but not at 54 weeks following vaccination.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Based on these results, a second trial was conducted which failed to show efficacy.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Merck tested V710, a vaccine targeting IsdB, in a blinded randomized trial in patients undergoing median sternotomy.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] The trial was terminated after a higher rate of multiorgan system failure–related deaths was found in the V710 recipients.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Vaccine recipients who developed *S. aureus* infection were five times more likely to die than control recipients who developed *S. aureus* infection.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Investigators have suggested that a multiple-antigen vaccine would be more effective, but a lack of biomarkers defining human protective immunity keep these proposals in the logical, but strictly hypothetical arena.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Antibodies show evidence against antimicrobial resistance.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Monoclonal antibodies (mAbs) target bacterial virulence factors, aiding in bacterial destruction through various mechanisms.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Three FDA-approved antibodies target *Bacillus anthracis* and *Clostridioides difficile* toxins.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Alternating therapy is a proposed method in which two or three antibiotics are taken in a rotation versus taking just one antibiotic such that bacteria resistant to one antibiotic are killed when the next antibiotic is taken.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Studies have found that this method reduces the rate at which antibiotic resistant bacteria emerge in vitro relative to a single drug for the entire duration.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Studies have found that bacteria that evolve antibiotic resistance towards one group of antibiotic may become more sensitive to others.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] This phenomenon can be used to select against resistant bacteria using an approach termed collateral sensitivity cycling, which has recently been found to be relevant in developing treatment strategies for chronic infections caused by *Pseudomonas aeruginosa*.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Despite its promise, large-scale clinical and experimental studies revealed limited evidence of susceptibility to antibiotic cycling across various pathogens.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Another concern is that practitioners may become reluctant to perform routine surgeries because of the increased risk of harmful infection.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Backup treatments can have serious side-effects; for example, antibiotics like aminoglycosides (such as amikacin, gentamicin, kanamycin, streptomycin, etc.) used for the treatment of drug-resistant tuberculosis and cystic fibrosis can cause respiratory disorders, deafness and kidney failure.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] The potential crisis at hand is the result of a marked decrease in industry research and development.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Poor financial investment in antibiotic research has exacerbated the situation.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] In 2011, Pfizer, one of the last major pharmaceutical companies developing new antibiotics, shut down its primary research effort, citing poor shareholder returns relative to drugs for chronic illnesses.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] However, small and medium-sized pharmaceutical companies are still active in antibiotic drug research.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] In particular, apart from classical synthetic chemistry methodologies, researchers have developed a combinatorial synthetic biology platform on single cell level in a high-throughput screening manner to diversify novel lanthipeptides.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] In the 5–10 years since 2010, there has been a change in the ways new antimicrobial agents are discovered and developed – principally via the formation of public-private funding initiatives.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Later stage clinical development is supported by the AMR Action Fund, which in turn is supported by multiple investors with the aim of developing 2–4 new antimicrobial agents by 2030.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] The discovery and development of new antimicrobial agents has been facilitated by regulatory advances, which have been principally led by the European Medicines Agency (EMA) and the Food and Drug Administration (FDA).
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] These processes are increasingly aligned although important differences remain and drug developers must prepare separate documents.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] New development pathways have been developed to help with the approval of new antimicrobial agents that address unmet needs such as the Limited Population Pathway for Antibacterial and Antifungal Drugs (LPAD).
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] These new pathways are required because of difficulties in conducting large definitive phase III clinical trials in a timely way.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Some of the economic impediments to the development of new antimicrobial agents have been addressed by reimbursement schemes that delink payment of antimicrobials from volume-based sales.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] The available classes of antifungal drugs are still limited but as of 2021 novel classes of antifungals are being developed and are undergoing various stages of clinical trials to assess performance.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Scientists have started using advanced computational approaches with supercomputers for the development of new antibiotic derivatives to deal with antimicrobial resistance.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Using antibiotic-free alternatives in bone infection treatment may help decrease the use of antibiotics and thus antimicrobial resistance.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] The bone regeneration material bioactive glass S53P4 has shown to effectively inhibit the bacterial growth of up to 50 clinically relevant bacteria including MRSA and MRSE.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] During the last decades, copper and silver nanomaterials have demonstrated appealing features for the development of a new family of antimicrobial agents.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Nanoparticles (1–100 nm) show unique properties and promise as antimicrobial agents against resistant bacteria.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Silver (AgNPs) and gold nanoparticles (AuNPs) are extensively studied, disrupting bacterial cell membranes and interfering with protein synthesis.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Zinc oxide (ZnO NPs), copper (CuNPs), and silica (SiNPs) nanoparticles also exhibit antimicrobial properties.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] However, high synthesis costs, potential toxicity, and instability pose challenges.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] To overcome these, biological synthesis methods and combination therapies with other antimicrobials are explored.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Similar to the situation in malaria therapy, where successful treatments based on ancient recipes have been found, there has already been some success in finding and testing ancient drugs and other treatments that are effective against AMR bacteria.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] One of the key tools identified by the WHO and others for the fight against rising antimicrobial resistance is improved surveillance of the spread and movement of AMR genes through different communities and regions.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Recent advances in high-throughput DNA sequencing as a result of the Human Genome Project have resulted in the ability to determine the individual microbial genes in a sample.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Along with the availability of databases of known antimicrobial resistance genes, such as the Comprehensive Antimicrobial Resistance Database (CARD) and ResFinder, this allows the identification of all the antimicrobial resistance genes within the sample – the so-called "resistome".
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] In doing so, a profile of these genes within a community or environment can be determined, providing information into how antimicrobial resistance is spreading through a population and allowing for the identification of resistance that is of concern.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Phage therapy is the therapeutic use of bacteriophages to treat pathogenic bacterial infections.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Phage therapy has many potential applications in human medicine as well as dentistry, veterinary science, and agriculture.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Phage therapy relies on the use of naturally occurring bacteriophages to infect and lyse bacteria at the site of infection in a host.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Due to current advances in genetics and biotechnology these bacteriophages can possibly be manufactured to treat specific infections.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Phages can be bioengineered to target multidrug-resistant bacterial infections, and their use involves the added benefit of preventing the elimination of beneficial bacteria in the human body.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Phages destroy bacterial cell walls and membrane through the use of lytic proteins which kill bacteria by making many holes from the inside out.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Bacteriophages can even possess the ability to digest the biofilm that many bacteria develop that protect them from antibiotics to effectively infect and kill bacteria.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Bioengineering can play a role in creating successful bacteriophages.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Understanding the mutual interactions and evolutions of bacterial and phage populations in the environment of a human or animal body is essential for rational phage therapy.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Bacteriophagics are used against antibiotic resistant bacteria in Georgia (George Eliava Institute) and in one institute in Wrocław, Poland.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Bacteriophage cocktails are common drugs sold over the counter in pharmacies in eastern countries.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] In Belgium, four patients with severe musculoskeletal infections received bacteriophage therapy with concomitant antibiotics.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] After a single course of phage therapy, no recurrence of infection occurred and no severe side-effects related to the therapy were detected.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Analysing AMR data at scale requires dedicated computational approaches, as routine microbiological data from clinical laboratories can be large, heterogeneous, and subject to varying local standards.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Several open-source tools have been developed to support this work.
[src:antimicrobial-resistance/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] The AMR package for R provides functions for standardising and analysing phenotypical resistance data, including interpretation of MIC and disk diffusion results against EUCAST and CLSI breakpoints, and calculation of resistance rates across patient populations.
